run rings around/round
Homonym Number:
Word Class: phrase
Sense Number:
Definition:to overcome or surpass (a person) easily; to easily better (a person) at; to beat hollow


Origin: [none]
Register:
Register 2:
Domain: [none]
Region: [none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes: ca1900 (well pre-WW1); orig. Aust/NZ? now in UK dictionaries unlabelled
Citations
Date:  0/0/1898
Source:  Austral English
Author:  MORRIS
Vol / Page:  390
Edition:
Quote:  Run Rings Round to run round: to beat out and out. A picturesque bit  of Australian slang. One runner runs straight to the goal, the other is so much better that he can run round and round his competitor, and yet reach the goal first. [1891]
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1941
Source:  NZ Slang
Author:  BAKER
Vol / Page:  38
Edition:
Quote:  [The Australasian] to run rings around a person, which can be used in both literal and figurative senses ... [On] January 3, 1940, the version to make rings round was used in a leader of the London Times. ... There is every reason to suspect that it came from the shearing shed ... to ring a shed and to be a ringer.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1966
Source:  English Language in Aust. & NZ, The
Author:  TURNER
Vol / Page:  51
Edition:
Quote:  A new chum ... would ... hear such colloquial expressions as to run rings round `to excel easily'.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1986
Source:  Off the Sheep's Back
Author:  RICHARDS
Vol / Page:  94
Edition:
Quote:  My new [95] friends warned me that he would `run rings' round the lot of us.
